result.execSummary:
The defendant Nathaniel J Burke was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • OWI (2nd), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Nathaniel J Burke in court with attorney Jamie J LaVora. Peter Hahn on behalf of  Paul Michael Hauer, appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: AMI

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  

AS TO COUNT 2:

Court ordered defendant to serve 60 days in the House of Correction consecutive to any other sentence; with goodtime credit, with release for work, inmate work assignments within the House of Correction, The Day Reporting Center, AODA Treatment and Childcare; with credit for 3 days (1/6/2016-1/8/2016) time served. - Provide DNA sample, if not already done.

Court ordered a payment plan in the amount of $50.00 per month with the first payment due on 07-01-2016 and additional payments due the first of each month thereafter.  If there are any missed payments any remaining balance will be due FORTHWITH and an immediate entry of a civil judgment is ordered by the court. Court orders defendant restricted to operation of vehicles equipped with an ignition interlock device for 12 months to commence upon eligibility to reinstate license. Ignition Interlock Exemption Order, signed.

AS TO COUNT 1:
Court ordered defendant to serve 7 MONTHS in the House of Correction consecutive to any other sentence;  release for work, inmate work assignments within the House of Correction, The Day Reporting Center, and AODA treatment; with credit for 0 days time served. No Childcare release will be allowed. Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring. 

COURT STAYED THE SENTENCE and placed defendant on probation for 18 MONTHS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety: No use or possession of alcohol or controlled substances without a valid prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment and successfully complete recommended treatment.  
- Department of Corrections must conduct drug and alcohol testing.
- No possession of any drug paraphernalia for personal use, manufacturing, delivering or for distribution.
- Seek/Maintain full time employment/school or a combination of both. 
- Fine is set at ZERO.
- Driver's License Suspension not imposed in count 1.
- Provide DNA sample, if not already done. 
- Pay all mandatory court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including the DNA surcharge, during the course of probation to the probation agent. Any remaining balance due at the end of probation will become immediately due or civil judgment to be entered.

Defendant examined as to plea, and entered a plea of guilty.  Court found defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived all constitutional rights. Plea questionnaire waiver of rights and addendum to plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulated to the criminal complaint as factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered into the record.  The Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon not to possess any firearms/body armor.    Court further advised defendant of voting ineligibility.
